{
  "dialogue_timestamps": [
    {
      "start_time": 0.0,
      "end_time": 1.96,
      "duration": 2.06,
      "audio_text": "Welcome to Two Minute Neuroscience, where I",
      "sequence_num": 1
    },
    {
      "start_time": 2.16,
      "end_time": 4.720000000000001,
      "duration": 2.66,
      "audio_text": "simplistically explain neuroscience topics in two minutes or less.",
      "sequence_num": 2
    },
    {
      "start_time": 4.96,
      "end_time": 7.58,
      "duration": 2.72,
      "audio_text": "In this installment, I will discuss the neuron.",
      "sequence_num": 3
    },
    {
      "start_time": 9.53,
      "end_time": 14.600000000000001,
      "duration": 5.07,
      "audio_text": "This is a brain. Estimates vary.",
      "sequence_num": 4
    },
    {
      "start_time": 14.72,
      "end_time": 15.620000000000001,
      "duration": 1.0,
      "audio_text": "85 billion neurons.",
      "sequence_num": 5
    },
    {
      "start_time": 16.72,
      "end_time": 19.24,
      "duration": 2.62,
      "audio_text": "The neuron is a nerve cell and it's the primary functional unit",
      "sequence_num": 6
    },
    {
      "start_time": 19.52,
      "end_time": 26.06,
      "duration": 6.54,
      "audio_text": "the nervous system. This is a generic image of a neuron. Neurons act",
      "sequence_num": 7
    },
    {
      "start_time": 26.24,
      "end_time": 28.08,
      "duration": 1.94,
      "audio_text": "version of a neuron that you'll often see in a textbook.",
      "sequence_num": 8
    },
    {
      "start_time": 29.47,
      "end_time": 37.379999999999995,
      "duration": 7.91,
      "audio_text": "The structures extending from the left side of the neuron that look a little bit like tree branches are called dendrites.",
      "sequence_num": 9
    },
    {
      "start_time": 38.16,
      "end_time": 44.4,
      "duration": 6.34,
      "audio_text": "There are receptors on dendrites that are designed to pick up signals from other neurons that come in the form of chemicals called neurotransmitters.",
      "sequence_num": 10
    },
    {
      "start_time": 44.9,
      "end_time": 54.919999999999995,
      "duration": 10.02,
      "audio_text": "Those signals picked up by dendrites cause electrical changes in a neuron that are interpreted in an area called the soma, or the cell body.",
      "sequence_num": 11
    },
    {
      "start_time": 55.28,
      "end_time": 56.98,
      "duration": 1.8,
      "audio_text": "DNA or genetic material of the cell.",
      "sequence_num": 12
    },
    {
      "start_time": 57.96,
      "end_time": 61.6,
      "duration": 3.74,
      "audio_text": "The soma takes all the information from the dendrites and puts it together in an area",
      "sequence_num": 13
    },
    {
      "start_time": 61.7,
      "end_time": 62.9,
      "duration": 1.3,
      "audio_text": "called the axon hillock.",
      "sequence_num": 14
    },
    {
      "start_time": 63.85,
      "end_time": 67.75,
      "duration": 4.0,
      "audio_text": "If the signal coming from the dendrites is strong enough, then a signal is sent to the",
      "sequence_num": 15
    },
    {
      "start_time": 67.85,
      "end_time": 70.31,
      "duration": 2.56,
      "audio_text": "next part of the neuron, which is called the axon.",
      "sequence_num": 16
    },
    {
      "start_time": 71.04,
      "end_time": 71.94000000000001,
      "duration": 1.0,
      "audio_text": "at this point, the",
      "sequence_num": 17
    },
    {
      "start_time": 72.24,
      "end_time": 73.36,
      "duration": 1.22,
      "audio_text": "signal is called an action potential.",
      "sequence_num": 18
    },
    {
      "start_time": 74.75,
      "end_time": 79.37,
      "duration": 4.72,
      "audio_text": "The action potential travels down the axon, which is covered with myelin, an insulatory",
      "sequence_num": 19
    },
    {
      "start_time": 79.47,
      "end_time": 81.78000000000002,
      "duration": 2.31,
      "audio_text": "material that helps to prevent the signal from getting out of the axon.",
      "sequence_num": 20
    },
    {
      "start_time": 82.99000000000001,
      "end_time": 87.43,
      "duration": 4.54,
      "audio_text": "The last step for the action potential is the axon terminals, also known as synaptic",
      "sequence_num": 21
    },
    {
      "start_time": 87.53,
      "end_time": 87.71000000000001,
      "duration": 0.28,
      "audio_text": "buttons.",
      "sequence_num": 22
    },
    {
      "start_time": 88.53,
      "end_time": 92.41000000000001,
      "duration": 3.98,
      "audio_text": "When the signal reaches the axon terminals, it can cause the release of neurotransmitter.",
      "sequence_num": 23
    },
    {
      "start_time": 93.23,
      "end_time": 95.89000000000001,
      "duration": 2.76,
      "audio_text": "These purple structures represent the dendrites of another neuron.",
      "sequence_num": 24
    },
    {
      "start_time": 96.39,
      "end_time": 99.87,
      "duration": 3.58,
      "audio_text": "When a neurotransmitter is released from axon terminals, it interacts with the receptors",
      "sequence_num": 25
    },
    {
      "start_time": 99.97,
      "end_time": 103.49000000000001,
      "duration": 3.62,
      "audio_text": "on the dendrites of the next neuron, and then the process repeats with the next neuron.",
      "sequence_num": 26
    }
  ],
